{"ts":"2026-06-27T22:42:43.565Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"tool","toolName":"read_files","toolCallId":"sn4t5ju4","output":[{"query":"/Users/ayushbansal/Documents/GitHub/hirezapp_landing_page/docs/PHASE_6_AWS_FINAL_SETUP.md","result":"  1 | # GFF AI Platform: Phase 6 AWS Production Deployment & Data Modeling Guide\n  2 | \n  3 | This document defines the enterprise AWS cloud migration strategy for the **GFF AI Platform** from the local Phase 5 sandbox. It specifies the exact schemas for three required DynamoDB tables, an S3 storage bucket, and the required environment parameters.\n  4 | \n  5 | ---\n  6 | \n  7 | ## 1. Cloud-Native Serverless Architecture\n  8 | \n  9 | ```\n 10 | +------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+\n 11 | |                               PHASE 6 ENTERPRISE AWS TOPOLOGY                                  |\n 12 | |  [ SECURE CLIENTS ] ==( HTTPS / TLS 1.3 )==> [ API GATEWAY ] ==> [ FASTAPI ON AWS LAMBDA ]    |\n 13 | |                                                                          |                     |\n 14 | |  [ S3 STORAGE BUCKET ] <--(Presigned URLs)-------------------------------+                     |\n 15 | |  (gff-portal-documents)                                                  v                     |\n 16 | |                                                                 [ AMAZON DYNAMODB ]            |\n 17 | |                                                                 - GFF_USERS                    |\n 18 | |                                                                 - GFF_CLIENTS                  |\n 19 | |                                                                 - GFF_PORTAL_ITEMS             |\n 20 | +------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+\n 21 | ```\n 22 | \n 23 | ---\n 24 | \n 25 | ## 2. Production DynamoDB Data Modeling\n 26 | \n 27 | Exactly **three** DynamoDB tables are used. Complex workspace and transactional entities are modeled inside a single-table architecture (`GFF_PORTAL_ITEMS`) using custom Partition Keys (`PK`) and Sort Keys (`SK`).\n 28 | \n 29 | ### 2.1. Table Map Overview\n 30 | | Table Name | Partition Key (PK) | Sort Key (SK) | Global Secondary Index (GSI) | Purpose |\n 31 | | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n 32 | | **`GFF_USERS`** | `email` (String) | *None* | *None* | Global user registry and access credentials. |\n 33 | | **`GFF_CLIENTS`** | `client_id` (String) | *None* | *None* | Enterprise customer accounts. |\n 34 | | **`GFF_PORTAL_ITEMS`** | `PK` (String) | `SK` (String) | `GSI1` (using `GSI1PK` & `GSI1SK`) | Multi-tenant workspace record store. |\n 35 | \n 36 | ### 2.2. Table Definition: `GFF_USERS`\n 37 | *   **Table Name**: `GFF_USERS`\n 38 | *   **Primary Key**: `email` (String)\n 39 | *   **Example Item**: `{\"email\": \"admin@client.com\", \"role\": \"admin\", \"client_id\": \"client_gff_01\"}`\n 40 | \n 41 | ### 2.3. Table Definition: `GFF_CLIENTS`\n 42 | *   **Table Name**: `GFF_CLIENTS`\n 43 | *   **Primary Key**: `client_id` (String)\n 44 | *   **Example Item**: `{\"client_id\": \"client_gff_01\", \"company_name\": \"Sovereign Logistics Corp\", \"tier\": \"ENTERPRISE\"}`\n 45 | \n 46 | ### 2.4. Single-Table Definition: `GFF_PORTAL_ITEMS`\n 47 | *   **Table Name**: `GFF_PORTAL_ITEMS`\n 48 | *   **Primary Key**: `PK` (String), `SK` (String)\n 49 | *   **GSI Name**: `GSI1` (using `GSI1PK` and `GSI1SK`)\n 50 | *   **Purpose**: Single-table design housing the 6 core operational models of the GFF AI Portal.\n 51 | \n 52 | #### Entity Mappings & Storage Patterns\n 53 | \n 54 | 1. **Projects**\n 55 |    - **`PK`**: `CLIENT#<client_id>` | **`SK`**: `PROJ#<project_id>`\n 56 |    - **`GSI1PK`**: `PROJ#<project_id>` | **`GSI1SK`**: `METADATA`\n 57 |    - **Attributes**: `name`, `status`, `progress`, `budget`, `created_at`\n 58 | \n 59 | 2. **AI Operations**\n 60 |    - **`PK`**: `CLIENT#<client_id>` | **`SK`**: `AIOPS#<ops_id>`\n 61 |    - **`GSI1PK`**: `PROJ#<project_id>` (links to project) | **`GSI1SK`**: `AIOPS#<ops_id>`\n 62 |    - **Attributes**: `name`, `status`, `agent_count`, `runtime_seconds`, `cpu_usage`, `memory_usage`\n 63 | \n 64 | 3. **Documents Metadata**\n 65 |    - **`PK`**: `CLIENT#<client_id>` | **`SK`**: `DOC#<doc_id>`\n 66 |    - **`GSI1PK`**: `PROJ#<project_id>` (retrieves files by project) | **`GSI1SK`**: `DOC#<doc_id>`\n 67 |    - **Attributes**: `title`, `s3_key`, `file_size`, `category`, `uploaded_by`, `uploaded_at`\n 68 | \n 69 | 4. **Invoices Metadata**\n 70 |    - **`PK`**: `CLIENT#<client_id>` | **`SK`**: `INV#<invoice_id>`\n 71 |    - **`GSI1PK`**: `BILLING_PERIOD#<year_month>` | **`GSI1SK`**: `INV#<invoice_id>`\n 72 |    - **Attributes**: `amount_usd`, `status`, `due_date`, `epochs_consumed`, `created_at`\n 73 | \n 74 | 5. **Support Tickets**\n 75 |    - **`PK`**: `CLIENT#<client_id>` | **`SK`**: `TICKET#<ticket_id>`\n 76 |    - **`GSI1PK`**: `STATUS#<status_code>` (supports dashboard queues) | **`GSI1SK`**: `TICKET#<ticket_id>`\n 77 |    - **Attributes**: `subject`, `priority`, `status_text`, `assigned_to`, `created_at`\n 78 | \n 79 | 6. **Governance Items**\n 80 |    - **`PK`**: `CLIENT#<client_id>` | **`SK`**: `GOV#<gov_id>`\n 81 |    - **`GSI1PK`**: `STANDARD#<compliance_standard>` | **`GSI1SK`**: `GOV#<gov_id>`\n 82 |    - **Attributes**: `control_name`, `status`, `remediation_notes`, `assessed_at`\n 83 | \n 84 | ---\n 85 | \n 86 | ## 3. Cloud Object Storage Setup (Amazon S3)\n 87 | \n 88 | *   **Bucket Reference**: `gff-portal-documents-prod`\n 89 | *   **Security Configurations**:\n 90 |     *   **Block Public Access**: Enabled.\n 91 |     *   **Encryption at Rest**: Enforced using KMS customer-managed keys (SSE-KMS).\n 92 |     *   **Secure Transport**: Restricts transport to TLS 1.3/HTTPS.\n 93 |     *   **Presigned Access**: Frontend uploads/downloads via short-lived pre-signed URLs generated by Lambda (valid for 15 minutes).\n 94 | \n 95 | ---\n 96 | \n 97 | ## 4. Required Deployment Environment Keys\n 98 | \n 99 | ### 4.1. Next.js Frontend Keys (`.env.production`)\n100 | ```env\n101 | NEXT_PUBLIC_API_BASE_URL=https://api.gff.ai/v1\n102 | NEXT_PUBLIC_APP_ENV=production\n103 | NEXT_PUBLIC_PORTAL_UPLOADS_ENABLED=true\n104 | NEXT_PUBLIC_S3_BUCKET_NAME=gff-portal-documents-prod\n105 | ```\n106 | \n107 | ### 4.2. FastAPI AWS Backend Keys (`backend/prod.env` / Lambda Variables)\n108 | ```env\n109 | PROJECT_NAME=\"GFF AI Enterprise Cloud Engine\"\n110 | API_V1_STR=\"/api/v1\"\n111 | ENVIRONMENT=\"production\"\n112 | CORS_ORIGINS=\"https://portal.gff.ai,https://admin.gff.ai\"\n113 | FRONTEND_BASE_URL=\"https://portal.gff.ai\"\n114 | AWS_REGION=us-east-1\n115 | AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID=production_aws_access_key_id\n116 | AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY=production_aws_secret_access_key\n117 | DYNAMODB_USERS_TABLE=GFF_USERS\n118 | DYNAMODB_CLIENTS_TABLE=GFF_CLIENTS\n119 | DYNAMODB_ITEMS_TABLE=GFF_PORTAL_ITEMS\n120 | DYNAMODB_ITEMS_TYPE_INDEX=GSI1\n121 | S3_DOCUMENTS_BUCKET=gff-portal-documents-prod\n122 | S3_DOCUMENTS_PREFIX=clients\n123 | JWT_SECRET=production_cryptographically_secure_256_bit_signature_key_2026\n124 | ACCESS_TOKEN_EXPIRE_MINUTES=1440\n125 | ```\n126 | \n127 | \n128 | ---\n129 | \n130 | ## 5. Seeded User Credentials (Final MVP Data)\n131 | \n132 | The system contains exactly **four** seeded user accounts covering the three standard RBAC roles (`gff_admin`, `client_admin`, `client_member`). All passwords, roles, and client associations are modeled to enable immediate high-fidelity secure testing.\n133 | \n134 | | Role | Email | Password | Associated Client | Notes |\n135 | | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n136 | | **`gff_admin`** | `gff_admin@gff.ai` | `password123` | *None* | Global platform administrator. Accesses the GFF Admin Panel. |\n137 | | **`client_admin`** | `client_admin@apex.com` | `password123` | `Apex Global Solutions` (ID: 1) | Enterprise client administrator. Full workspace management for Client 1. |\n138 | | **`client_member`** | `client_member@apex.com` | `password123` | `Apex Global Solutions` (ID: 1) | Client 1 standard user. Limited operational access inside Client 1 workspace. |\n139 | | **`client_member`** | `client@chevron.com` | `chevron_secure_pass_2026` | `Sovereign Logistics Corp` (ID: 2) | Client 2 standard user. Used to verify cross-tenant security and upload/download boundaries in smoke tests. |\n140 | \n141 | These credentials can be used both locally (via SQLite/mock fallbacks) and in the production cloud (AWS DynamoDB) once the environment is initialized and seeded using:\n142 | ```bash\n143 | npm run backend:seed\n144 | ```\n145 | ","success":true},{"query":"/Users/ayushbansal/Documents/GitHub/hirezapp_landing_page/backend/app/main.py","result":"  1 | import time\n  2 | from fastapi import FastAPI, Request\n  3 | from fastapi.middleware.cors import CORSMiddleware\n  4 | from fastapi.responses import RedirectResponse, JSONResponse\n  5 | from fastapi.exceptions import RequestValidationError\n  6 | from starlette.exceptions import HTTPException as StarletteHTTPException\n  7 | from contextlib import asynccontextmanager\n  8 | \n  9 | from .core.config import settings\n 10 | from .db import init_db\n 11 | from .api.routes import api_router\n 12 | \n 13 | # Lifespan for FastAPI (creates DB tables on startup)\n 14 | @asynccontextmanager\n 15 | async def lifespan(app: FastAPI):\n 16 |     # Initialize SQLite database tables automatically on launch for a local MVP setup\n 17 |     init_db()\n 18 |     yield\n 19 | \n 20 | app = FastAPI(\n 21 |     title=settings.PROJECT_NAME,\n 22 |     description=\"GFF AI Enterprise Local MVP Backend Platform.\",\n 23 |     version=\"1.0.0\",\n 24 |     lifespan=lifespan\n 25 | )\n 26 | \n 27 | @app.exception_handler(StarletteHTTPException)\n 28 | async def http_exception_handler(request: Request, exc: StarletteHTTPException):\n 29 |     # Map status code to friendly error category\n 30 |     error_map = {\n 31 |         400: \"Bad Request\",\n 32 |         401: \"Unauthorized\",\n 33 |         403: \"Forbidden\",\n 34 |         404: \"Not Found\",\n 35 |         409: \"Conflict\",\n 36 |         422: \"Validation Error\",\n 37 |     }\n 38 |     err_title = error_map.get(exc.status_code, \"Error\")\n 39 |     return JSONResponse(\n 40 |         status_code=exc.status_code,\n 41 |         content={\n 42 |             \"success\": False,\n 43 |             \"error\": err_title,\n 44 |             \"message\": exc.detail,\n 45 |             \"detail\": exc.detail\n 46 |         }\n 47 |     )\n 48 | \n 49 | @app.exception_handler(RequestValidationError)\n 50 | async def validation_exception_handler(request: Request, exc: RequestValidationError):\n 51 |     # Extract details\n 52 |     errors = exc.errors()\n 53 |     # Format a simple message\n 54 |     messages = []\n 55 |     for err in errors:\n 56 |         loc = \" -> \".join(str(loc) for loc in err.get(\"loc\", []))\n 57 |         msg = err.get(\"msg\", \"invalid value\")\n 58 |         messages.append(f\"{loc}: {msg}\")\n 59 |     detailed_message = \"; \".join(messages) or \"Validation failed\"\n 60 |     \n 61 |     return JSONResponse(\n 62 |         status_code=422,\n 63 |         content={\n 64 |             \"success\": False,\n 65 |             \"error\": \"Validation Error\",\n 66 |             \"message\": detailed_message,\n 67 |             \"detail\": detailed_message,\n 68 |             \"errors\": errors\n 69 |         }\n 70 |     )\n 71 | \n 72 | # CORS configuration\n 73 | origins = settings.get_cors_origins()\n 74 | \n 75 | app.add_middleware(\n 76 |     CORSMiddleware,\n 77 |     allow_origins=origins,\n 78 |     allow_credentials=True,\n 79 |     allow_methods=[\"*\"],\n 80 |     allow_headers=[\"*\"],\n 81 | )\n 82 | \n 83 | # Request timing middleware (for enterprise-grade logging and performance tracking)\n 84 | @app.middleware(\"http\")\n 85 | async 